{"id":"1703.00628","submitter":"Suman Chatterjee","authors":"Suman Chatterjee, S. Bharadwaj and V. R. Marthi","title":"Simulating the z = 3.35 HI 21-cm visibility signal for the Ooty Wide\n  Field Array(OWFA)","comments":"To appear in the Special Section of the JAA on the Ooty Wide Field\n  Array","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s12036-017-9433-1","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The upcoming Ooty Wide Field Array (OWFA) will operate at $326.5 \\, {\\rm\nMHz}$ which corresponds to the redshifted 21-cm signal from neutral hydrogen\n(HI) at z = 3.35. We present two different prescriptions to simulate this\nsignal and calculate the visibilities expected in radio-interferometric\nobservations with OWFA. In the first method we use an input model for the\nexpected 21-cm power spectrum to directly simulate different random\nrealizations of the brightness temperature fluctuations and calculate the\nvisibilities. This method, which models the HI signal entirely as a diffuse\nradiation, is completely oblivious to the discrete nature of the astrophysical\nsources which host the HI. While each discrete source subtends an angle that is\nmuch smaller than the angular resolution of OWFA, the velocity structure of the\nHI inside the individual sources is well within reach of OWFA's frequency\nresolution and this is expected to have an impact on the observed HI signal.\nThe second prescription is based on cosmological N-body simulations. Here we\nidentify each simulation particle with a source that hosts the HI, and we have\nthe freedom to implement any desired line profile for the HI emission from the\nindividual sources. Implementing a simple model for the line profile, we have\ngenerated several random realizations of the complex visibilities. Correlations\nbetween the visibilities measured at different baselines and channels provides\nan unique method to quantify the statistical properties of the \\HI signal. We\nhave used this to quantify the results of our simulations, and explore the\nrelation between the expected visibility correlations and the underlying HI\npower spectrum.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Mar 2017 05:21:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-03-29"}
